WEBVTT

00:01.101 --> 00:05.938
[ jazz playing ]

00:05.940 --> 00:09.208
[ indistinct conversations ]

00:15.749 --> 00:16.982
I'll take my usual,

00:16.984 --> 00:20.819
And, uh, whatever these
fine young ladies are drinking.

00:20.821 --> 00:24.023
Actually, I'll take that against
the money you already owe me.

00:24.025 --> 00:25.324
Come on, man. It's like that?

00:25.326 --> 00:27.326
Yeah, izzy,
it's like that, my man.

00:27.328 --> 00:29.862
Relax, rudy.
Somebody's ship just came in.

00:29.864 --> 00:33.599
Next time I'm in here,
I'm buying for <i>everyone.</i>

00:33.601 --> 00:36.802
What kind of crazy scheme
you come up with this time?

00:38.238 --> 00:39.805
Rain check on those drinks.

00:39.807 --> 00:43.075
Good luck cashing it in.

00:43.077 --> 00:44.343
[ song ends,
cheers and applause ]

00:44.345 --> 00:46.378
Man: [ amplified voice ]
thank you. We'll be back in 10.

00:46.380 --> 00:50.416
Keep smiling, 'cause you're
gonna be the one paying it.

00:50.418 --> 00:51.383
That's right.

00:51.385 --> 00:55.120
I've finally found it --
a smoking gun.

00:55.122 --> 00:56.688
Now the world's gonna know

00:56.690 --> 01:00.359
What kind of businessman
al rainey is.

01:03.463 --> 01:06.632
[ horn blares in distance ]

01:06.634 --> 01:09.334
[ train tracks rumbling ]

01:16.076 --> 01:19.378
[ siren wailing in distance ]

01:26.019 --> 01:27.319
[ liquid sloshes ]

01:29.856 --> 01:31.623
[ groans ]

01:36.763 --> 01:38.330
[ train tracks rumbling ]

01:38.332 --> 01:40.332
[ mozart's <i>"don giovanni,</i>
<i>a cenar teco"</i> playing ]

01:40.334 --> 01:42.734
<i>¶ don giovanni</i>

01:42.736 --> 01:43.902
[ whistles blows ]

01:43.904 --> 01:49.875
¶ a cenar teco

01:49.877 --> 01:52.911
¶ m'invita-- <i>¶</i>
<i>[ record needle scratches ]</i>

01:52.913 --> 01:58.083
Rules are rules, henry.
No opera before 8:00 a.M.

01:58.085 --> 01:59.318
It's a quarter past 10:00.

01:59.320 --> 02:01.854
Oh. Guess we should
open the store.

02:01.856 --> 02:03.789
Late night?

02:03.791 --> 02:05.324
No. Early morning.

02:05.326 --> 02:09.228
I'll be okay after
I iron out a few kinks.

02:09.230 --> 02:11.630
<i>[ charlie parker's</i>
<i>"crazeology" playing ]</i>
<i>ah!</i>

02:11.632 --> 02:13.332
[ grunts ]

02:13.334 --> 02:16.401
You should loosen up yourself.
Looking a tad stiff.

02:16.403 --> 02:20.539
I'm just not a fan
of this new popular music.

02:20.541 --> 02:22.674
So pardon me
if I'm not going to

02:22.676 --> 02:25.177
Put my thing down, flip it,
and reverse it.

02:25.179 --> 02:28.213
Wrong genre. That's rap.
This is jazz.

02:28.215 --> 02:29.615
It's all the same to me.

02:29.617 --> 02:32.985
I mean, where's the melody?
The harmony? The structure?

02:32.987 --> 02:35.220
What you young people
are listening to these days

02:35.222 --> 02:36.822
Is not music.
It's just noise.

02:36.824 --> 02:38.090
What's that?

02:38.092 --> 02:39.892
You want it louder?

02:39.894 --> 02:41.360
[ volume turns up ]

02:42.795 --> 02:45.964
[ telephone rings ]

02:45.966 --> 02:48.700
[ loudly ] dr. Henry morgan.

02:48.702 --> 02:49.902
Oh, thank god!

02:49.904 --> 02:53.505
Yes, I know exactly where
that is. Right.

02:53.507 --> 02:55.841
I'll be there right now.
[ hangs up receiver ]

02:55.843 --> 02:57.709
Well, duty calls.

02:57.711 --> 03:00.646
They just found another body
uptown.

03:00.648 --> 03:03.315
And please try
to keep the music down.

03:03.317 --> 03:04.783
I won't have you disturbing
our neighbors.

03:04.785 --> 03:07.920
Yeah, <i>whatever...Dad.</i>
<i>[ door bells jingle ]</i>

03:07.922 --> 03:09.688
<i>¶</i>

03:11.658 --> 03:14.726
[ siren whoops,
police radio chatter ]

03:14.728 --> 03:15.994
Jo: Got anything?

03:15.996 --> 03:18.197
Possible flame source.

03:18.199 --> 03:19.531
[ camera shutter clicking ]

03:19.533 --> 03:20.933
Huh.

03:20.935 --> 03:22.834
Possible combustible material.

03:22.836 --> 03:24.503
Unless this guy was drinking
rocket fuel,

03:24.505 --> 03:26.338
There had to be
something else.

03:26.340 --> 03:28.207
Henry:
An accelerant of some kind.

03:29.842 --> 03:33.545
Whatever incinerated this man
burned very hot and very fast.

03:33.547 --> 03:36.715
Better to burn out
than fade away.

03:36.717 --> 03:38.016
How poetic.

03:38.018 --> 03:40.018
Oh, not me. Neil young.

03:40.020 --> 03:41.553
Oh, he's a poet?

03:42.422 --> 03:44.289
Henry, we need a cause of death.

03:44.291 --> 03:45.691
Pretty obvious, ain't it?

03:45.693 --> 03:48.627
Manner of death is never
obvious. Context is everything.

03:51.497 --> 03:54.933
5 to 1 he'll say
he was murdered.

03:56.436 --> 03:57.703
This man was murdered!

03:57.705 --> 04:00.539
No fair.
He always says that.

04:00.541 --> 04:02.908
Then incinerated
<i>after</i> his death.

04:02.910 --> 04:05.510
Wow. That's a new one.
How did you know all that?

04:05.512 --> 04:08.347
There's no sign of soot
in his mouth.

04:10.316 --> 04:12.684
Or the nostrils.

04:12.686 --> 04:15.554
If this man were alive
when he was burned,

04:15.556 --> 04:17.589
He would've inhaled
super-heated air,

04:17.591 --> 04:19.558
Causing significant fire damage

04:19.560 --> 04:21.126
And soot in the nostrils
and mouth.

04:21.128 --> 04:23.128
Okay, but we still need
evidence of foul play

04:23.130 --> 04:26.598
To turn this into a homicide,
and...All I see is ash.

04:26.600 --> 04:27.833
You see, that's where
you're wrong.

04:27.835 --> 04:29.735
Beneath this carbonized
layer of skin

04:29.737 --> 04:33.405
Lie immaculate strata
of muscles and soft tissue.

04:33.407 --> 04:34.740
Burning a body
doesn't destroy evidence,

04:34.742 --> 04:37.175
As one might assume,
but preserves it.

04:37.177 --> 04:39.811
This man's killer
has done us a favor.

04:39.813 --> 04:41.880
Oh, yeah? Tell him that.

04:45.818 --> 04:48.887
¶

04:52.625 --> 04:55.927
<i>Henry: No matter</i>
<i>how we live or die,</i>

04:55.929 --> 04:57.863
<i>We all end the same --</i>

04:57.865 --> 04:59.865
<i>In silence.</i>
<i>[ clanking ]</i>

04:59.867 --> 05:01.967
<i>All of our hopes and dreams</i>
<i>in life</i>

05:01.969 --> 05:05.103
<i>Become mere echoes</i>
<i>of a tale cut short.</i>

05:05.105 --> 05:06.972
<i>But if we're lucky enough,</i>

05:06.974 --> 05:09.775
<i>Our stories live on.</i>

05:09.777 --> 05:11.877
<i>Our song finds voice</i>
<i>in the hearts</i>

05:11.879 --> 05:15.180
<i>Of those who remember us</i>
<i>and loved us.</i>

05:15.182 --> 05:17.082
No sign of smoke inhalation.

05:17.084 --> 05:20.218
He was already dead
when his car caught on fire?

05:20.220 --> 05:21.987
The petechiae there
and there

05:21.989 --> 05:24.089
Are consistent
with strangulation.

05:24.091 --> 05:26.358
It's like he was
strangled with...

05:26.360 --> 05:30.395
I don't know.
A-a thin wire, maybe?

05:33.266 --> 05:35.734
Hmm. Forceps.

05:42.742 --> 05:45.711
[ squish ]

05:46.646 --> 05:49.414
A reed
from a musical instrument.

05:49.416 --> 05:52.884
Woodwind --
saxophone or clarinet.

05:52.886 --> 05:54.219
Wire...

05:54.221 --> 05:56.655
Piano wire, perhaps.

05:56.657 --> 05:59.091
Hmm. Gauge of a treble g.

05:59.093 --> 06:02.260
[ humming in key of g ]

06:02.262 --> 06:04.062
[ humming off-key ]

06:04.064 --> 06:05.831
[ continues humming in g ]

06:05.833 --> 06:07.966
I can't --
I just can't hear it.

06:07.968 --> 06:11.403
[ both hum in tune ]

06:11.405 --> 06:12.537
[ clears throat ]

06:12.539 --> 06:14.539
You two startin' up
a barbershop quartet?

06:14.541 --> 06:17.442
Just demonstrating that
I have perfect pitch.

06:17.444 --> 06:19.644
Only 1 in 10,000 people
have it.

06:19.646 --> 06:21.012
As for
an I.D. On the victim --

06:21.014 --> 06:24.082
I already got one
off the vehicle's v.I.N. Number.

06:24.084 --> 06:26.618
Isaiah williams. Age 29.

06:26.620 --> 06:28.120
Yes, his size
and weight match

06:28.122 --> 06:30.555
What this man's measurements
would have been

06:30.557 --> 06:31.690
Prior to being burned.

06:31.692 --> 06:34.326
So, uh... [ clears throat ]
time of death?

06:34.328 --> 06:35.460
Lucas?

06:35.462 --> 06:37.162
Oh! Almost forgot.

06:38.297 --> 06:40.132
[ squish ]
[ groans ]

06:40.134 --> 06:43.602
The longer the body is dead,
the more it cools.

06:43.604 --> 06:46.605
Only this man wasn't
98.6 degrees when he died.

06:46.607 --> 06:48.907
He was super heated,
cooked inside the car.

06:48.909 --> 06:52.411
We need to know the temperature
at which the accelerant burned

06:52.413 --> 06:54.146
And the duration of the fire
in order to know

06:54.148 --> 06:57.549
And from that figure, we can
approximate his time of death.

06:57.551 --> 07:01.686
Oh. Look...What I found.

07:04.490 --> 07:06.625
What is that?
Cellulose.

07:06.627 --> 07:08.827
Celluloid acetate,
to be precise.

07:08.829 --> 07:11.897
As in old film stock.
It's crazy flammable.

07:11.899 --> 07:14.166
This is the accelerant
that caused that fire

07:14.168 --> 07:16.034
To burn so hot so fast.

07:16.036 --> 07:17.903
Who even uses film anymore?

07:17.905 --> 07:21.173
Uh, nobody, you know.
Just steven spielberg,

07:21.175 --> 07:23.975
Wes anderson, myself.

07:23.977 --> 07:26.311
Yep, I was a film major,

07:26.313 --> 07:29.714
And I did some important
experimental films in college,

07:29.716 --> 07:33.718
Mostly horror, but I also
dabbled in horror-erotica.

07:33.720 --> 07:35.854
Tasteful, though.

07:35.856 --> 07:37.923
The victim's next of kin
is here. Shall I send her?

07:37.925 --> 07:40.659
Yes. Thanks.
Mind if we use your office?

07:40.661 --> 07:43.428
Oh, yes, by all means.
I'll, uh, cover the body.

07:43.430 --> 07:46.398
You know, I could always
bust out the old film projector

07:46.400 --> 07:47.566
And have a little screening...

07:47.568 --> 07:49.935
Or not.

07:53.072 --> 07:55.140
Henry: We found these

07:55.142 --> 07:57.108
On his person.

07:57.110 --> 07:58.977
[ sighs ] it could be.

07:58.979 --> 08:01.413
Izzy always wore
a lot of jewelry.

08:01.415 --> 08:03.281
Some real, some fake.
Just...

08:03.283 --> 08:04.749
Not always the same stuff.

08:04.751 --> 08:06.551
As soon as he'd get
into some money trouble,

08:06.553 --> 08:08.887
He'd have to pa--

08:15.428 --> 08:17.128
You recognize it?

08:19.699 --> 08:21.233
That's a sax reed.

08:21.235 --> 08:23.835
[ voice breaks ] it's izzy.
That's my brother's.

08:23.837 --> 08:27.572
Ever since he was 8, he...

08:27.574 --> 08:30.008
He'd never go anywhere
without one in his mouth.

08:31.244 --> 08:32.944
So he was a musician.

08:32.946 --> 08:37.482
Um...Our father was
the real player.

08:37.484 --> 08:40.151
Yeah, still is, I suppose.

08:40.153 --> 08:42.888
Who's your father?

08:42.890 --> 08:45.156
You ever hear of
pepper evans?

08:45.158 --> 08:46.958
No. Who -- who is he?

08:46.960 --> 08:51.229
The best jazz musician
you've never heard of.

08:52.999 --> 08:55.433
When was the last time
you spoke to your brother?

08:55.435 --> 08:58.670
Last night.
Called from a bar.

08:58.672 --> 09:00.672
Oh. Any idea which one?

09:00.674 --> 09:03.808
Yeah, there was, uh, music
in the background.

09:03.810 --> 09:06.144
[ voice breaking ]
izzy was all excited.

09:06.146 --> 09:07.612
Said dad gave him something

09:07.614 --> 09:10.215
That was gonna put him
on easy street.

09:11.417 --> 09:15.053
Do you know where we might
be able to locate pepper?

09:16.522 --> 09:18.623
Last I heard,

09:18.625 --> 09:23.828
He has a standing gig
at 125th and broadway.

09:25.598 --> 09:26.865
[ train tracks clacking ]

09:26.867 --> 09:30.168
[ saxophone playing slow jazz ]

09:34.373 --> 09:35.507
Excuse me.

09:35.509 --> 09:37.609
Pepper evans?
[ stops playing ]

09:37.611 --> 09:39.377
[ helicopter whirring
in distance ]

09:39.379 --> 09:40.779
Who's asking?

09:42.648 --> 09:45.083
Detective?

09:47.286 --> 09:49.087
Homicide?

09:49.089 --> 09:53.658
We'd like to ask you a few
questions about your son isaiah.

09:55.528 --> 09:56.895
What happened to my boy?

09:56.897 --> 09:59.931
[ train wheels clacking ]

10:06.472 --> 10:08.139
Is there anyone

10:08.141 --> 10:11.576
That would've wanted
to hurt your son in any way?

10:11.578 --> 10:13.545
Not that I can think of.

10:13.547 --> 10:17.482
But izzy -- he wasn't
no boy scout either.

10:17.484 --> 10:21.820
Your daughter said you gave izzy
something the night he died.

10:21.822 --> 10:23.355
You talked to ella?

10:23.357 --> 10:25.790
What'd you give him?

10:27.627 --> 10:31.496
Just -- just a bunch
of my old...

10:31.498 --> 10:33.298
Reel-to-reel audiotapes.

10:33.300 --> 10:35.533
Audiotapes.

10:35.535 --> 10:38.536
So it wasn't film in izzy's car.

10:38.538 --> 10:39.838
What was on the tapes?

10:39.840 --> 10:42.007
Probably nothing.

10:42.009 --> 10:45.944
But izzy -- he lived for
those old recordings,

10:45.946 --> 10:48.046
So I put 'em in my old case.

10:48.048 --> 10:49.547
Case?

10:49.549 --> 10:51.983
For my horn.

10:51.985 --> 10:54.219
[ chuckles ]
it was grafton alligator,

10:54.221 --> 10:57.188
And I was just using it
to catch coins.

10:57.190 --> 10:59.691
He called ella
from a nightclub.

10:59.693 --> 11:02.060
Izzy liked clubs.

11:02.062 --> 11:04.696
There was jazz
playing in the background.

11:04.698 --> 11:07.799
Not many of them left.

11:07.801 --> 11:09.334
Maybe dutch's?

11:09.336 --> 11:12.237
If we have any more questions...

11:18.611 --> 11:22.047
You know where to find me.

11:24.316 --> 11:25.950
[ door opens and closes ]

11:25.952 --> 11:28.219
Abe: You met pepper evans?!

11:28.221 --> 11:29.421
Oh, he was the greatest!

11:29.423 --> 11:31.923
You know, I think I got
one of his albums right here.

11:31.925 --> 11:33.758
I mean, that guy --
he was a prodigy.

11:33.760 --> 11:37.328
Playing with lionel hubbard's
band at the age of 14, yeah.

11:37.330 --> 11:39.264
You don't -- you don't know
who lionel hubbard is?

11:39.266 --> 11:41.599
Huh?
The guy who wrote "6 a.M."

11:41.601 --> 11:43.301
One of the biggest names
in jazz.

11:43.303 --> 11:44.969
Yeah, pepper -- he played
with all of them.

11:44.971 --> 11:47.138
Yeah, miles, coltrane, dizzy.

11:47.140 --> 11:48.506
When are you going to stop
saying the names

11:48.508 --> 11:50.041
Of people I've never
heard of?

11:50.043 --> 11:52.777
[ scoffs ] henry, they're
titans. They're legends.

11:52.779 --> 11:54.312
They're gods.

11:54.314 --> 11:57.182
Jazz is truly
an american art form.

11:57.184 --> 11:59.818
Now I'm gonna go
on the record and say...
Don't say it.

11:59.820 --> 12:02.487
Jazz is
our classical music.

12:02.489 --> 12:06.057
Failed as a father!
Have I taught you nothing?

12:06.059 --> 12:08.326
Some things are not taught.
They're felt.

12:08.328 --> 12:09.794
You know, I got it
with my other records.

12:09.796 --> 12:11.329
I'll be right back.

12:11.331 --> 12:15.300
[ playing chopin's "nocturne in
e-flat major, op. 9, no. 2" ]

12:19.872 --> 12:22.307
[ plays discordant keys ]

12:22.309 --> 12:24.275
No, no, no. Abraham, look.

12:24.277 --> 12:25.744
It's like this.

12:25.746 --> 12:29.481
¶

12:29.483 --> 12:31.382
Or like this, huh?

12:31.384 --> 12:34.185
¶

12:34.187 --> 12:35.854
Now focus.
[ man and woman arguing
in distance ]

12:35.856 --> 12:37.088
Classical music is

12:37.090 --> 12:38.857
The foundation
of civilized society.

12:38.859 --> 12:40.325
[ muffled crash,
woman screams in distance ]

12:40.327 --> 12:41.659
Man: [ muffled ]
what are you thinking?!

12:41.661 --> 12:43.561
[ woman shouts indistinctly ]
and the sign of a refined mind.

12:43.563 --> 12:44.829
It's boring.

12:44.831 --> 12:46.297
Abe, the <i>notes.</i>

12:46.299 --> 12:48.767
[ banging on door ]

12:48.769 --> 12:49.934
Man: Damn woman!

12:49.936 --> 12:52.137
Keep practicing.

12:53.539 --> 12:57.575
Sorry. Me and the old lady --
we having a disagreement.

12:57.577 --> 13:00.145
Oh, it's me.
Red from next door.

13:00.147 --> 13:01.613
Well, you're a doctor, right?
Can you help me out?

13:01.615 --> 13:03.615
I got a gig tonight.

13:03.617 --> 13:05.350
Yes. Of course.
Come in. Come in.

13:09.388 --> 13:10.855
[ door closes ]

13:10.857 --> 13:12.590
He's seen blood before.
Right.

13:12.592 --> 13:14.993
Please have a seat.

13:21.734 --> 13:24.736
Ah. I'm afraid
it's gonna need stitches.

13:24.738 --> 13:27.172
Uh, bear with me a moment.

13:30.709 --> 13:31.876
Chopin, huh?

13:31.878 --> 13:34.012
You've heard of him?
Oh, yeah.

13:34.014 --> 13:36.014
He's one of the greats.

13:36.016 --> 13:37.682
And it bores me
half to death.

13:37.684 --> 13:39.150
[ chuckles ]

13:39.152 --> 13:40.752
You ever try playing jazz?

13:40.754 --> 13:42.253
I don't have
the sheet music.

13:42.255 --> 13:44.355
Well, that's the beautiful thing
about it.

13:44.357 --> 13:45.523
You don't need it.

13:45.525 --> 13:48.860
Now all you do is
take a theme like this...

13:48.862 --> 13:52.163
Old and crusty chopin here...

13:53.032 --> 13:56.434
[ plays "nocturne
in e-flat major, op. 9, no. 2" ]

13:56.436 --> 13:58.336
And make it your own.

13:58.338 --> 14:01.973
[ playing
jazz-infused rendition ]

14:09.615 --> 14:11.783
This may, uh, sting a bit.
[ stops playing ]

14:11.785 --> 14:15.286
[ pepper playing sonny rollins'
<i>"alfie's theme differently " ]</i>

14:20.259 --> 14:21.860
It's remarkable.

14:21.862 --> 14:23.328
Ah, I knew
you'd come around.

14:23.330 --> 14:25.563
Can't act like a philistine
forever, can you?

14:25.565 --> 14:28.566
No, I mean the resemblance
between young pepper and izzy.

14:28.568 --> 14:29.968
It's uncanny.
Oh.

14:29.970 --> 14:32.403
<i>¶</i>

14:32.405 --> 14:37.075
His son was at a show
on the night he was murdered.

14:37.077 --> 14:39.510
Ever heard of a club
called dutch's?

14:39.512 --> 14:40.745
Oh,    <i>yes.</i>

14:40.747 --> 14:41.880
It's where all the hepcats

14:41.882 --> 14:43.681
Used to smoke
their reefer cigarettes.

14:43.683 --> 14:44.816
Get with the times, henry.

14:44.818 --> 14:47.285
Dutch's? Dutch's closed
decades ago.

14:47.287 --> 14:49.187
No, the place
is called rudy's now.

14:49.189 --> 14:50.321
No, it's a great place.

14:50.323 --> 14:52.824
Yeah, it's up
on lenox and 140th.

14:52.826 --> 14:56.628
<i>¶</i>

15:00.666 --> 15:03.001
Jo: Isaiah williams.

15:03.003 --> 15:05.303
You remember seeing him in here
Friday night?

15:05.305 --> 15:06.971
No. No, doesn't look familiar.

15:06.973 --> 15:08.773
I find that hard to believe.

15:08.775 --> 15:11.676
Clearly you know pepper evans.

15:11.678 --> 15:15.480
That izzy is the spirit
and image of his father.

15:15.482 --> 15:19.350
The young pepper evans
pictured there on your wall.

15:19.352 --> 15:21.185
You know, we could always
subpoena the footage

15:21.187 --> 15:23.521
From the a.T.M.
Across the street,

15:23.523 --> 15:24.756
Go through it face by face.

15:24.758 --> 15:26.391
When we find out who was here
on Friday night --

15:26.393 --> 15:28.726
Okay, okay. I might've seen him.
It was a busy night.

15:28.728 --> 15:31.062
I-I just forgot, that's all.

15:31.064 --> 15:32.997
Look, I-I should get back,
get ready for tonight.

15:32.999 --> 15:34.198
I-I got a real hot act, okay?

15:34.200 --> 15:36.134
Before you go,
might I trouble you

15:36.136 --> 15:40.271
For a glass of your macallan 30,
please?

15:41.307 --> 15:42.707
It's worth it.

15:48.480 --> 15:49.814
[ whispers ] henry!

15:49.816 --> 15:51.482
What the hell?

15:51.484 --> 15:53.851
What you were hiding
behind the bar

15:53.853 --> 15:54.986
And couldn't help looking at

15:54.988 --> 15:56.554
Every time izzy's name
was mentioned.

15:56.556 --> 15:57.956
I don't suppose
this is alligator?

15:57.958 --> 15:59.657
Look, just give me it back.

15:59.659 --> 16:01.025
Pepper evans' initials.

16:01.027 --> 16:03.294
Izzy had it with him
the night he was murdered.

16:03.296 --> 16:05.163
The night he was in your bar.

16:05.165 --> 16:07.365
Look, izzy owed me money,

16:07.367 --> 16:08.566
A-and I took the case
as collateral,

16:08.568 --> 16:11.302
But I did not kill him.
You took the case how?

16:11.304 --> 16:14.339
While izzy was busy
running his mouth,

16:14.341 --> 16:15.707
Bragging about
how he was gonna be rich,

16:15.709 --> 16:17.675
I snuck out and I-I took it
out of his car.

16:17.677 --> 16:18.910
What else was in there?

16:18.912 --> 16:20.745
Uh...

16:20.747 --> 16:22.580
Some old reel-to-reel tapes.

16:22.582 --> 16:26.617
[ plucking notes
on stand-up bass ]

16:28.854 --> 16:29.988
What's wrong?

16:29.990 --> 16:32.056
[ plays off-key note ]

16:32.058 --> 16:33.524
It's a tad sharp.

16:33.526 --> 16:35.360
So tune it.

16:38.530 --> 16:40.565
[ scrape ]

16:41.867 --> 16:43.801
It's a new string.

16:43.803 --> 16:45.870
Recently replaced.

16:45.872 --> 16:48.806
Izzy was killed with
what I thought was a piano wire.

16:48.808 --> 16:50.174
Treble g.

16:50.176 --> 16:52.010
So what are you sayin'?

16:52.012 --> 16:55.346
Right note, wrong instrument.

17:01.653 --> 17:02.920
Things aren't looking too good
for you, rudy.

17:02.922 --> 17:05.990
I got a bar full of witnesses
who saw you confront izzy

17:05.992 --> 17:07.225
The night he was killed.

17:07.227 --> 17:09.027
We also found
the victim's stolen property

17:09.029 --> 17:10.628
In your possession,
which you lied about.

17:10.630 --> 17:13.698
Killing a guy
that owed me money?

17:13.700 --> 17:14.832
That's no way to get paid.

17:14.834 --> 17:16.434
You knew he wasn't good for it.

17:16.436 --> 17:18.369
<i>Jo: He came into that bar.</i>

17:18.371 --> 17:20.438
<i>He was waving his money</i>
<i>all around.</i>

17:20.440 --> 17:22.106
<i>Hanson: Money you knew</i>
<i>he didn't have.</i>

17:22.108 --> 17:23.841
That made you mad.
Didn't it, rudy?

17:23.843 --> 17:26.644
And took the only thing
that was worth something.

17:26.646 --> 17:27.612
Look, I wasn't the only one

17:27.614 --> 17:29.147
Whose face izzy was in
that night.

17:29.149 --> 17:32.383
Did he happen to tell you where
all this money was coming from?

17:32.385 --> 17:35.219
Ever since I've known him,
izzy claimed that his pops

17:35.221 --> 17:37.555
Was the one who really wrote
"6 a.M.,"

17:37.557 --> 17:39.957
That lionel hubbard,
jazz legend,

17:39.959 --> 17:41.125
<i>Cheated him out of a single.</i>

17:41.127 --> 17:43.194
Can you imagine that?

17:43.196 --> 17:46.898
Killing someone
<i>literally</i> for a song?

17:46.900 --> 17:48.733
It's not just a song.

17:48.735 --> 17:53.171
"6 a.M." changed everything.

17:53.173 --> 17:55.306
That track broke
all the rules,

17:55.308 --> 17:57.675
Changing keys
and time signatures

17:57.677 --> 18:00.445
As if the person who wrote it
had so much joy inside his heart

18:00.447 --> 18:04.482
He couldn't pick just one way
to let it out.

18:07.820 --> 18:09.020
[ door opens ]

18:09.022 --> 18:12.423
[ telephone ringing
in distance ]
lieutenant?

18:12.425 --> 18:15.626
I've never heard you speak
so passionately about anything.

18:15.628 --> 18:17.161
Why don't I have
time of death?

18:17.163 --> 18:19.730
That man's alibi is
hinging on it, doctor.

18:19.732 --> 18:21.299
How hard can it be?

18:21.301 --> 18:22.900
To be honest with you,
uh, quite hard.

18:22.902 --> 18:25.470
Normally, it would be
a question of temperature.

18:25.472 --> 18:28.272
But in this case,
it's a matter of thermodynamics.

18:28.274 --> 18:29.841
Lucas: 160 degrees!
You see --

18:29.843 --> 18:31.309
That's it. Sorry.

18:31.311 --> 18:33.244
That's the temperature
that izzy's body reached

18:33.246 --> 18:34.712
When it was cooked
inside the car.

18:34.714 --> 18:37.248
The fire burned
approximately half an hour.

18:37.250 --> 18:38.649
Lucas, did you use
the standard

18:38.651 --> 18:41.385
Cooling rate after death
of 1.5 degrees per hour?

18:41.387 --> 18:43.121
Yes.

18:43.123 --> 18:44.722
Okay, so legal time of death --

18:44.724 --> 18:47.959
3:15, with the temperature,
the corrective factor,

18:47.961 --> 18:50.661
Meaning...
The precise time of death
is exactly...

18:50.663 --> 18:51.996
9:00.
11:58.

18:51.998 --> 18:53.431
11:58?

18:53.433 --> 18:54.866
Yes.

18:54.868 --> 18:59.303
Izzy's body temperature rose to
160 degrees in half an hour.

18:59.305 --> 19:01.672
It would've dropped
equally as fast.

19:01.674 --> 19:03.708
Thermodynamics. Sorry.

19:03.710 --> 19:06.777
Meaning our club owner rudy
couldn't have killed him.

19:06.779 --> 19:10.481
Who have him tending bar
till 3:00 in the morning.

19:10.483 --> 19:12.416
Either way, I don't think
he's good for the murder.

19:12.418 --> 19:14.418
Okay, so what are you thinking,
detective?

19:14.420 --> 19:16.621
Rudy said that izzy had
audiotapes in his car.

19:16.623 --> 19:19.490
So what if izzy had found
the proof that he needed,

19:19.492 --> 19:21.826
And now that proof has burned up
with him inside the car?

19:21.828 --> 19:23.227
Yeah, only now,
there's no way of knowing

19:23.229 --> 19:25.796
What was actually <i>on</i>
<i>pepper's old audiotapes.</i>

19:25.798 --> 19:27.565
Although there is a way
of figuring out

19:27.567 --> 19:29.167
Who might have destroyed them --

19:29.169 --> 19:31.235
Whoever owns the rights
to "6 a.M."

19:31.237 --> 19:33.004
Al rainey.

19:33.006 --> 19:35.439
C.E.O. Of dovebird records.

19:35.441 --> 19:38.743
He owns
lionel hubbard's publishing.

19:38.745 --> 19:42.446
He's a guy who's made a career
off of fleecing musicians.

19:42.448 --> 19:43.581
How -- how did you...

19:43.583 --> 19:45.917
My nephew was one of them.

19:45.919 --> 19:47.985
What?

19:47.987 --> 19:51.789
I'm learning that you have all
sorts of unexpected dimensions.

19:51.791 --> 19:56.394
We'll go pay rainey
a visit. Come on.

19:57.763 --> 20:00.364
So...Big music buff, huh?

20:00.366 --> 20:02.133
I'm a cinephile myself.

20:02.135 --> 20:04.402
Yeah, more of an auteur,
actually.

20:04.404 --> 20:07.138
If you ever wanted to check out
any of my student...

20:07.140 --> 20:09.941
It's -- coming.

20:09.943 --> 20:12.276
First thing tomorrow morning?
Yeah.

20:13.412 --> 20:14.812
[ siren whooping in distance ]

20:14.814 --> 20:17.548
Al: Sure. I saw izzy
there that night.

20:17.550 --> 20:20.218
He was there for the same reason
everybody was --

20:20.220 --> 20:22.553
To watch these boys
do their thing.

20:22.555 --> 20:24.322
Jo: How well
did you know izzy?

20:24.324 --> 20:25.823
Well enough to wipe his nose

20:25.825 --> 20:27.792
While he was
still wearing diapers.

20:27.794 --> 20:30.628
Damn shame what happened
to that boy.

20:30.630 --> 20:32.763
His old man was
a solid session guy for me

20:32.765 --> 20:35.533
Back in the day.
Did he mention anything
that night

20:35.535 --> 20:37.802
About royalties for a song
his father wrote?

20:37.804 --> 20:39.303
You mean "6 a.M."?

20:39.305 --> 20:40.671
If izzy's mouth was moving,

20:40.673 --> 20:43.574
Chances are that story was
coming out of it.

20:43.576 --> 20:46.911
Witnesses also told us
the night izzy was killed

20:46.913 --> 20:48.646
That he confronted you,

20:48.648 --> 20:50.514
Saying he had found
some kind of proof.

20:50.516 --> 20:52.650
Izzy had a hundred versions
of that story.

20:52.652 --> 20:55.186
Hard to keep track
of all of 'em.

20:55.188 --> 20:58.122
So pepper <i>didn't</i> write
"6 a.M."?

20:58.124 --> 20:59.991
Wanna know how I know?

20:59.993 --> 21:02.493
Because that track was
recorded in that room,

21:02.495 --> 21:03.995
With me sittin'
in this booth.

21:03.997 --> 21:06.197
A lot of people were smoking
a lot of stuff that night,

21:06.199 --> 21:09.667
But I was stone-cold sober,
so believe me when I tell you,

21:09.669 --> 21:11.669
Lionel hubbard
wrote that song.

21:11.671 --> 21:15.406
Or if you don't believe me,
you can dig through my vault.

21:15.408 --> 21:18.609
But you not gonna find pepper's
name anywhere near that master.

21:18.611 --> 21:20.478
You still have
the old master?

21:20.480 --> 21:22.713
Well, yes and no.

21:22.715 --> 21:26.083
It's all digital now,
lossless compression.

21:26.085 --> 21:27.952
It's a brave new world.

21:27.954 --> 21:28.953
That's smart.

21:28.955 --> 21:31.389
I hear that
the old reel-to-reel tapes

21:31.391 --> 21:34.025
Can be quite flammable.

21:35.594 --> 21:37.828
I'd be happy to show you
the vault.

21:37.830 --> 21:42.767
Let you listen to the original
"6 a.M." session if you want.

21:42.769 --> 21:45.403
Man: All right,
let's take it from the top.

21:46.972 --> 21:49.073
Bud gray quintet, day one.

21:49.075 --> 21:51.108
[ click ]

21:51.110 --> 21:52.910
All right, from the top.

21:52.912 --> 21:57.481
[ playing frank basile's
"the high desert" ]

22:06.325 --> 22:09.627
¶

22:13.665 --> 22:16.967
[ playing erroll garner's
"boogie woogie boogie" ]

22:20.872 --> 22:23.908
All right, little man,
your turn.

22:23.910 --> 22:27.078
No, you all right,
you all right.

22:27.080 --> 22:30.481
Look, forget about the notes.
Jazz is about how you feel.

22:30.483 --> 22:32.183
Now you feeling
cold and lonely,

22:32.185 --> 22:34.418
Play it sad like this.
[ playing riff slow-tempo ]

22:34.420 --> 22:37.655
You feeling fat and happy,
you play it big,

22:37.657 --> 22:39.824
Play it loud.
[ playing riff up-tempo]

22:39.826 --> 22:43.961
Now you feeling hot and mad,
murder them keys, boy.

22:43.963 --> 22:44.795
Murder 'em.

22:44.797 --> 22:48.766
[ playing riff
up-tempo loudly ]

22:48.768 --> 22:51.869
¶

22:54.039 --> 22:56.507
Go, man, go! [ laughs ]

22:56.509 --> 22:58.409
¶

22:58.411 --> 23:02.346
Make your hair stand up,
don't it? [ laughs ]

23:02.348 --> 23:04.115
Thank you, mr. Rainey.

23:04.117 --> 23:06.384
Not a problem.

23:06.386 --> 23:09.153
Ah. Were you a tad close
to a fire?

23:09.155 --> 23:11.122
Excuse me?

23:11.124 --> 23:12.923
The hairs on your arm --

23:12.925 --> 23:14.225
They've recently been
singed off.

23:14.227 --> 23:18.562
Yeah, well, uh, I did a little
barbecuing this weekend.

23:19.831 --> 23:23.200
Well, I trust you two
can find your way out.

23:23.202 --> 23:24.301
A few burned arm hairs?

23:24.303 --> 23:25.870
That's not enough
to bring him in.

23:25.872 --> 23:28.572
I don't suppose there was
anything on the master recording

23:28.574 --> 23:30.474
That proved pepper
authored the track?

23:30.476 --> 23:33.010
No. Maybe izzy just
overestimated

23:33.012 --> 23:34.345
His father's talent.

23:34.347 --> 23:36.480
Or else died
trying to immortalize it.

23:36.482 --> 23:38.382
Okay, let's consider
the possibility

23:38.384 --> 23:40.017
That izzy was telling
the truth,

23:40.019 --> 23:41.852
That he did find
some sort of proof.

23:41.854 --> 23:44.221
Well, whatever he did find
would have burnt up

23:44.223 --> 23:45.756
With him in the car...

23:45.758 --> 23:49.493
Remember what I said about
fire preserving evidence?

23:49.495 --> 23:52.296
You wanna take another look
at izzy's car?

23:52.298 --> 23:56.634
Yes. I think it's time
we performed an <i>auto-topsy.</i>

23:56.636 --> 23:58.836
[ under breath ] wow.

23:58.838 --> 24:01.172
So you really think
we're gonna have better luck

24:01.174 --> 24:03.340
Than the arson team pulling
something out of here?

24:03.342 --> 24:05.543
By recreating the crime...
Lucas?

24:05.545 --> 24:06.977
Yep?
You're my victim.

24:06.979 --> 24:07.912
Every day.

24:07.914 --> 24:09.780
All right, lucas,
front seat.

24:09.782 --> 24:13.651
You would be hiding in the back,
waiting to surprise izzy.

24:13.653 --> 24:16.921
[ clears throat ]
so I'm a big man --

24:16.923 --> 24:19.957
Al rainey's size. I would have
to duck down like this.

24:19.959 --> 24:22.026
Okay, and I'm just chillin'
up here,

24:22.028 --> 24:24.762
Acting like I've never seen
a horror movie before?

24:24.764 --> 24:27.531
Not checking the backseat
for a deranged psychopath?

24:27.533 --> 24:29.900
Sorry.

24:29.902 --> 24:32.703
If I were to slip a bass string
around your neck,

24:32.705 --> 24:33.871
How do you stop me?

24:33.873 --> 24:35.773
Okay, I couldn't get my hangs
under the string,

24:35.775 --> 24:37.208
So I'd go for your hands?
Yes, very good.

24:37.210 --> 24:38.742
[ straining voice ]
all right, squeeze harder.

24:38.744 --> 24:40.678
I work method. Come on.
[ grunts ]

24:40.680 --> 24:43.280
There you go.
I fight, fight, fight.

24:43.282 --> 24:46.350
[ grunting ]

24:46.352 --> 24:47.551
Aha.

24:47.553 --> 24:49.286
[ exhales ] what?

24:49.288 --> 24:52.957
I was just starting
to feel my character.

24:52.959 --> 24:55.292
If izzy knocked something
off the killer

24:55.294 --> 24:57.094
While he struggled,

24:57.096 --> 24:59.563
It could be buried
under the melted remains

24:59.565 --> 25:00.831
Of these pleather seats.

25:00.833 --> 25:03.033
And if a burnt car
acts like a burnt body...

25:03.035 --> 25:05.903
Let's see what's underneath
the skin.

25:05.905 --> 25:07.638
Lucas, scalpel.

25:19.584 --> 25:21.552
A cuff link...

25:21.554 --> 25:23.521
Perfectly preserved.

25:26.892 --> 25:27.958
"d.B."

25:27.960 --> 25:32.930
Huh. David bowie,
daniel boone, d.B. Cooper,

25:32.932 --> 25:34.431
Doobie brothers.

25:34.433 --> 25:36.300
You're getting warmer,
lucas.

25:36.302 --> 25:38.536
Dovebird records.

25:38.538 --> 25:40.671
[ unzips ]

25:44.876 --> 25:48.379
[ indistinct conversations ]

25:48.381 --> 25:49.747
It's about time.

25:49.749 --> 25:51.882
I've been sitting here
for over an hour.

25:51.884 --> 25:53.884
Let's get to it, then.

25:53.886 --> 25:56.720
I think you killed
izzy williams, mr. Rainey.

25:56.722 --> 25:59.990
We have six witnesses
who saw you exit rudy's

25:59.992 --> 26:03.193
The same time as izzy's death.

26:03.195 --> 26:06.196
His story about you cheating
his father pepper

26:06.198 --> 26:07.631
Out of a hit song,

26:07.633 --> 26:08.966
Well, you stand
to lose more money

26:08.968 --> 26:12.136
Than most people make
their entire lives.

26:14.639 --> 26:15.673
I think we both know

26:15.675 --> 26:17.741
You're gonna have to do better
than that.

26:17.743 --> 26:19.944
I believe we can.

26:26.751 --> 26:30.621
You've seen that cuff link
before, haven't you?

26:30.623 --> 26:33.057
Found it in izzy's car.

26:33.059 --> 26:36.894
The only thing I care
to look at now is my lawyer.

26:36.896 --> 26:38.429
He should be here by now.

26:38.431 --> 26:40.064
We're executing a search warrant

26:40.066 --> 26:42.666
For your residence,
along with dovebird records.

26:42.668 --> 26:45.269
Now either you killed izzy
yourself

26:45.271 --> 26:46.303
Or you know who did.

26:46.305 --> 26:49.206
Either way, you are looking
guilty as hell.

26:49.208 --> 26:50.207
[ door opens ]

26:50.209 --> 26:53.143
Are you planning on
charging my client

26:53.145 --> 26:54.745
With a crime?
[ door closes ]

26:54.747 --> 26:57.915
If not, I don't know what
we're doing here.
[ briefcase thuds ]

26:57.917 --> 27:03.354
I'm entitled to hold on
to your client for 72 hours,

27:03.356 --> 27:07.725
And I intend to enjoy
every one of those hours.

27:07.727 --> 27:11.428
30 years
of dovebird records history.
[ telephone ringing ]

27:11.430 --> 27:12.763
Grab a shovel.

27:12.765 --> 27:15.199
Bit of a change of pace
from my regular duties.

27:15.201 --> 27:18.168
Yeah, all hands on deck, pal.
Lieutenant's orders.

27:18.170 --> 27:22.773
We're looking for anything tying
pepper evans to "6 a.M." --

27:22.775 --> 27:24.108
A certificate of authorship

27:24.110 --> 27:26.210
Would certainly give us
a motive on al.

27:26.212 --> 27:33.817
There is no rhyme or reason
to any of this stuff.

27:33.819 --> 27:36.286
[ classical piano playing ]

27:36.288 --> 27:39.823
[ playing
schumann's "etudes, op. 13" ]

27:42.327 --> 27:44.728
[ knock on door, stops playing ]

27:49.434 --> 27:50.567
[ door squeaks ]

27:50.569 --> 27:54.672
[ sighs ] you caught me
practicing a little myself.

27:54.674 --> 27:57.007
Is today's abe's lesson?
I'm terribly sorry.

27:57.009 --> 27:58.909
He's not here.
I know.

27:58.911 --> 28:01.612
No, I just stopped by
to say bye.

28:01.614 --> 28:03.580
I see. Please, come in.

28:03.582 --> 28:09.753
See, I wanted to tell little man
goodbye in person, but, uh...

28:13.291 --> 28:15.726
I got a 6-month gig
in <i>paris.</i>

28:15.728 --> 28:18.429
Yeah, let's just hope
the french girls

28:18.431 --> 28:21.031
Aren't as hot-tempered
as the american ones.

28:21.033 --> 28:23.967
Well,
I'm sorry to hear that.

28:23.969 --> 28:27.337
But I'm happy for you,
of course.

28:27.339 --> 28:28.972
Abe will be disappointed.

28:28.974 --> 28:30.774
Just keep him practicing.

28:30.776 --> 28:33.177
He got an ear for jazz,
that boy.

28:33.179 --> 28:36.180
I only wish I could help him
cultivate it.

28:36.182 --> 28:39.249
All I did
was light a match.

28:39.251 --> 28:42.052
Now it's up to you
to hand him the torch

28:42.054 --> 28:43.787
And let him find
his own way.

28:43.789 --> 28:45.389
Let him become
his own man.

28:45.391 --> 28:46.790
Hmm.

28:46.792 --> 28:48.792
Is that what your father
did for you?

28:48.794 --> 28:51.528
[ laughs ]

28:51.530 --> 28:52.930
Hell, no!

28:52.932 --> 28:55.466
Why do you think I know
it's the right thing to do?

28:55.468 --> 28:58.001
[ latches click open ]

29:04.275 --> 29:05.676
One for the road?

29:05.678 --> 29:08.045
That's handy.

29:08.047 --> 29:10.881
We musicians are like
bedouins.

29:10.883 --> 29:12.349
We move
where the wind moves.

29:12.351 --> 29:15.686
Everything I need
is inside this case.

29:15.688 --> 29:18.088
[ papers rustling ]

29:18.090 --> 29:20.691
Where's
pepper's saxophone case?

29:20.693 --> 29:22.126
Huh?

29:22.128 --> 29:23.494
[ grunting ]

29:23.496 --> 29:24.962
Uh...

29:24.964 --> 29:27.498
[ latches click ]

29:27.500 --> 29:29.199
What are you...

29:36.374 --> 29:39.309
Whoa. Whoa. Uh...

29:48.920 --> 29:51.321
I believe we found
our master tape...

29:51.323 --> 29:53.924
And that motive.

29:55.193 --> 29:58.462
[ indistinct conversations ]

29:58.464 --> 30:02.166
Tell me you've changed your mind
about detaining my client.

30:07.305 --> 30:09.006
What's that?

30:09.008 --> 30:11.074
It's the original recording
of "6 a.M."

30:11.076 --> 30:13.544
Proof that izzy
was telling the truth

30:13.546 --> 30:14.945
The night he was killed.

30:14.947 --> 30:16.346
What's he talking about?

30:16.348 --> 30:20.417
So you're telling me
you somehow managed

30:20.419 --> 30:23.220
To dig up the original master
of "6 a.M."?

30:23.222 --> 30:26.089
Izzy hid it in
his father's saxophone case --

30:26.091 --> 30:29.226
Somewhere he knew
it would be safe.

30:29.228 --> 30:32.162
Care for a listen,
mr. Rainey?

30:32.164 --> 30:35.465
Or you could sit in this room
alone in silence

30:35.467 --> 30:37.034
For the next 67 hours.

30:37.036 --> 30:38.969
[ click, whirring ]

30:38.971 --> 30:42.272
[ static and warping sound ]

30:45.977 --> 30:47.644
[ reece clears throat ]

30:47.646 --> 30:50.614
[ static continues ]

30:53.985 --> 30:56.787
[ whirring ]

30:56.789 --> 30:59.556
[ static continues ]

31:02.060 --> 31:04.928
I don't know about you...

31:04.930 --> 31:08.765
But I don't hear no hit single.

31:08.767 --> 31:11.368
[ laughs ]
[ hits table ]

31:14.005 --> 31:16.273
I can't dance to that.
[ snapping fingers ]

31:16.275 --> 31:18.075
[ laughs ]

31:18.077 --> 31:20.210
[ clicks off ]

31:20.212 --> 31:23.046
Al: Can we go home now?

31:26.684 --> 31:29.253
Detective?

31:29.255 --> 31:30.487
[ telephone ringing
in distance ]

31:30.489 --> 31:33.223
Mr. Evans. Um...

31:33.225 --> 31:36.793
Please...Have a seat.

31:36.795 --> 31:38.362
What can I do for you?

31:38.364 --> 31:41.498
It's funny how loss
creeps up on you.

31:46.771 --> 31:49.940
You haven't figured out
who killed my son yet, have you?

31:49.942 --> 31:55.245
No, no, but we might
have the "why."

31:55.247 --> 31:57.147
We believe that izzy
thought he had proof

31:57.149 --> 31:58.749
You wrote "6 a.M."

31:58.751 --> 32:02.119
It's possible that's why
he was killed.
What?

32:02.121 --> 32:03.687
The old tapes
that you gave him.

32:03.689 --> 32:06.256
I gotta ask you,
mr. Evans --

32:06.258 --> 32:09.927
Is it true?
Did you write it?

32:14.265 --> 32:15.265
I did.

32:15.267 --> 32:20.003
Cut it the day
after ella was born.

32:20.005 --> 32:23.840
Hmm.
Ella was a colicky baby.

32:23.842 --> 32:27.210
She cried day and night.

32:27.212 --> 32:30.047
I left the studio
to help her mother.

32:30.049 --> 32:32.015
Came back three days later.

32:32.017 --> 32:34.885
They had written me
out of everything.

32:34.887 --> 32:37.688
Why didn't you fight it?

32:37.690 --> 32:39.756
Take al to court.

32:39.758 --> 32:43.660
What difference
does it make?

32:43.662 --> 32:45.629
My son's dead.

32:46.631 --> 32:49.700
I never should have told him
that story.

32:54.272 --> 32:57.174
Um...
Where did you find that?

32:57.176 --> 33:00.577
In your son's car.
You recognize it?

33:02.513 --> 33:04.614
Mr. Evans?

33:10.321 --> 33:13.623
No, ma'am. You have yourself
a nice day.

33:19.931 --> 33:22.132
This thing hasn't seen
a lot of love

33:22.134 --> 33:24.534
Over the last --
I don't know -- 20 years.

33:24.536 --> 33:27.137
The emulsion has
separated from the base.

33:27.139 --> 33:28.672
What does that
even mean?

33:28.674 --> 33:32.876
Oh. This must be how it feels
to be...Well, you.

33:32.878 --> 33:36.079
Kinda feels good
being the expert.

33:36.081 --> 33:37.614
If you wouldn't mind...
Huh?

33:37.616 --> 33:41.585
Illuminating me on the subject
of audio recordings --

33:41.587 --> 33:42.452
Happy to help, doc.

33:42.454 --> 33:44.488
Look, you can tell
the tape is damaged

33:44.490 --> 33:46.690
If you know what
you're looking for.

33:46.692 --> 33:47.858
You see these uneven edges?

33:47.860 --> 33:50.494
There's two layers to
these old magnetic tapes,

33:50.496 --> 33:53.030
And once they come apart,
you're left with diddily-squat.

33:53.032 --> 33:56.099
And there's no way to recover
what was recorded on the tape?

33:56.101 --> 33:58.068
No, these things are
older than 8-tracks.

33:58.070 --> 34:00.037
Genuine antiques.

34:01.172 --> 34:04.174
Then we have
one more chance.

34:04.176 --> 34:05.742
[ timer dings ]

34:07.412 --> 34:10.947
[ oven door closes,
pan clatters ]

34:10.949 --> 34:12.549
Please, reassure me
one last time

34:12.551 --> 34:14.384
That this is
a legitimate process.

34:14.386 --> 34:15.585
Hey, you don't think
I'd take any chances

34:15.587 --> 34:18.455
With the original recording
of "6 a.M." huh?

34:18.457 --> 34:20.290
Of all the antiques
I've ever handled,

34:20.292 --> 34:21.825
This one
is truly priceless.

34:21.827 --> 34:26.029
This reel is suffering
from sticky-shed syndrome.

34:26.031 --> 34:27.297
Baking the tape...

34:27.299 --> 34:30.267
Fuses the two layers
back together again.

34:30.269 --> 34:31.501
Dare I ask how
you came about

34:31.503 --> 34:33.070
This particular area
of expertise?

34:33.072 --> 34:34.938
Transferring
old dead bootlegs.

34:34.940 --> 34:38.041
Another seminal band
you couldn't stomach, remember?

34:38.043 --> 34:41.278
I will disown you if you ever
don those tie-dyed pants again.

34:41.280 --> 34:43.346
Maybe we should open
a bottle of wine.

34:43.348 --> 34:45.749
Spark one up.
Oh, all right, fine, fine.

34:45.751 --> 34:47.150
You know, kill the moment.

34:47.152 --> 34:51.054
Now look, hey, who would have
thought you and I,

34:51.056 --> 34:53.957
About to rewrite
jazz history?

34:53.959 --> 34:55.125
[ clatter ]

34:55.127 --> 34:58.295
Abe baked the tape!

34:58.297 --> 35:00.163
It's as good as new,

35:00.165 --> 35:02.165
Like a phoenix rising
from the ashes,

35:02.167 --> 35:04.134
It brought the original
recording back to life.

35:04.136 --> 35:06.136
Baked? Like in an oven?

35:06.138 --> 35:07.437
Henry, please tell me

35:07.439 --> 35:10.240
You did not take evidence home
and cook it.

35:10.242 --> 35:12.776
Yes, but it worked.

35:12.778 --> 35:17.781
All right, betty crocker.
Play it.

35:17.783 --> 35:18.949
[ click, whirring ]

35:18.951 --> 35:21.852
<i>Man: And we're...Rolling.</i>

35:21.854 --> 35:23.553
<i>What do you</i>
<i>wanna play first, lionel?</i>

35:23.555 --> 35:26.256
<i>Lionel: Hey, how about that</i>
<i>new one of yours, pepper?</i>

35:26.258 --> 35:27.757
<i>I smell a hit single.</i>

35:27.759 --> 35:29.459
<i>Hey'd why'd you decide</i>
<i>to call it "6 a.M." anyhow?</i>

35:29.461 --> 35:32.462
<i>Pepper: That's when</i>
<i>my baby girl ella was born.</i>

35:32.464 --> 35:34.798
<i>Happiest hour of my life.</i>

35:34.800 --> 35:37.300
<i>'cause she came out</i>
<i>looking like her mama.</i>

35:37.302 --> 35:38.702
<i>[ laughter ]</i>
<i>well, I ain't much to look at,</i>

35:38.704 --> 35:41.037
<i>But at least they don't</i>
<i>call me "doughboy."</i>

35:41.039 --> 35:42.739
<i>[ laughter ]</i>

35:42.741 --> 35:44.774
<i>Yeah. [ laughs ]</i>
<i>all right, all right, boys,</i>

35:44.776 --> 35:47.444
<i>I'll count it down.</i>
<i>1, 2, 3.</i>

35:47.446 --> 35:52.616
<i>[ "6 a.M." playing ]</i>
<i>and there's our motive.</i>

35:52.618 --> 35:54.084
[ music warps off ]
proof that pepper
wrote the song.

35:54.086 --> 35:55.552
Let's move on rainey.

35:55.554 --> 35:57.053
Lieu...

35:57.055 --> 35:59.289
Lieu, wait.
Pepper was here today,

35:59.291 --> 36:01.992
And he seemed sure
that al didn't kill izzy,

36:01.994 --> 36:04.361
But he did recognize
the cuff links.
So did al.

36:04.363 --> 36:07.697
What if "d.B."
doesn't stand for "dovebird"?

36:07.699 --> 36:09.032
What if they're
the killer's initials?

36:09.034 --> 36:11.568
They still don't fit any of
our current suspects, though.

36:11.570 --> 36:13.303
D.B...

36:13.305 --> 36:15.639
D.B. "doughboy."

36:15.641 --> 36:18.642
Pepper called lionel hubbard
"doughboy" on the recording.

36:18.644 --> 36:21.311
Now lionel would have had
a motive to kill izzy.

36:21.313 --> 36:23.380
That song made him
a household name.

36:23.382 --> 36:25.015
Too bad he's been dead
15 years.

36:25.017 --> 36:28.118
Okay, maybe somebody inherited
lionel hubbard's cuff links

36:28.120 --> 36:31.188
And the recording rights
to "6 a.M."
like who, jo?

36:31.190 --> 36:33.857
The son. He had a son,
bud gray.

36:33.859 --> 36:36.259
Damn fine musician himself.

36:36.261 --> 36:39.362
<i>Man: Bud gray quintet,</i>
<i>day one.</i>

36:39.364 --> 36:41.932
Bud gray and his band
were recording at al's studio.

36:41.934 --> 36:45.502
They were playing at rudy's
the night izzy was murdered.

36:45.504 --> 36:47.571
It wasn't al, even though
the marks on his arms suggest

36:47.573 --> 36:49.739
That he might have burned
izzy's body.

36:49.741 --> 36:51.541
Bud gray is our killer.

36:51.543 --> 36:52.609
[ cheers and applause ]

36:52.611 --> 36:53.877
Man: [ amplified voice ]
let's hear it

36:53.879 --> 36:56.479
For the bud gray quintent.

36:56.481 --> 36:59.783
[ frank basile's
"modern inventions" playing ]

37:06.224 --> 37:09.826
¶

37:21.272 --> 37:24.507
¶

37:24.509 --> 37:28.278
[ cheers and applause ]

37:29.513 --> 37:32.282
Okay, you take the front
and the exits.

37:32.284 --> 37:34.251
You take the exterior alleys.

37:34.253 --> 37:36.953
[ cheers and applause ]

37:40.858 --> 37:44.461
¶

37:46.597 --> 37:48.732
[ cocks gun ]
you don't wanna do this!

37:48.734 --> 37:51.568
Let me go.
He killed my boy,

37:51.570 --> 37:54.204
And I can't let him
get away with it.
[ grunts ]

37:54.206 --> 37:56.706
What about your daughter?

37:56.708 --> 37:59.409
The police are here
to arrest bud.

37:59.411 --> 38:02.012
This gig is his last.

38:02.014 --> 38:05.949
¶

38:05.951 --> 38:07.717
[ music stops ]

38:07.719 --> 38:11.087
You still have time
to be ella's father.

38:11.089 --> 38:14.457
I was gone half her life.

38:14.459 --> 38:16.760
She's never gonna speak
to me again.

38:16.762 --> 38:19.095
We know why you wrote
"6 a.M."

38:19.097 --> 38:20.297
[ gasps ]

38:20.299 --> 38:22.299
Now she will, too.

38:22.301 --> 38:24.834
Shouldn't you at least
give her a chance?

38:27.338 --> 38:30.440
[ handcuffs rattle ]

38:32.810 --> 38:34.711
[ exhales ]

38:37.181 --> 38:40.750
[ crying ]

38:46.123 --> 38:48.858
[ continues crying ]

38:55.733 --> 38:58.001
[ siren whooping in distance ]

38:58.003 --> 39:01.671
The search of his hotel room
turned up the other cuff link.

39:01.673 --> 39:03.640
Guy knew it was over.
He gave us everything.

39:03.642 --> 39:05.208
[ receiver clatters ]

39:05.210 --> 39:06.710
Just got off the phone
with the a.D.A.

39:06.712 --> 39:08.278
Looks like a slam dunk.
That's great.

39:08.280 --> 39:09.279
What about al rainey?

39:09.281 --> 39:10.747
According
to bud's signed statement,

39:10.749 --> 39:13.383
Al knew izzy had proof
pepper wrote "6 a.M.,"

39:13.385 --> 39:14.417
Not lionel hubbard.

39:14.419 --> 39:15.952
Al told bud
to take care of it,

39:15.954 --> 39:17.253
And then he helped burn
izzy's body,

39:17.255 --> 39:19.656
What he thought was the proof.
We just picked up al.

39:19.658 --> 39:22.392
Nice work, you two.

39:22.394 --> 39:24.661
[ indistinct conversations ]

39:24.663 --> 39:26.629
You know,
I still don't get it.

39:26.631 --> 39:29.699
Bud gray had a record deal,
whole career ahead of him.

39:29.701 --> 39:32.702
Why would he kill a guy
over royalties of one song?

39:32.704 --> 39:34.971
He didn't want his father,
the great lionel hubbard,

39:34.973 --> 39:38.575
To go down in jazz history
as a fraud.

39:38.577 --> 39:41.010
[ speaks inaudibly ]

39:42.680 --> 39:46.983
Jo: Thanks for coming in.
I thought you should have this.

39:48.786 --> 39:50.120
I don't care
about the money.

39:50.122 --> 39:53.423
Whatever's on it has caused
my family a lot of pain.

39:53.425 --> 39:56.226
Okay. I just...

39:56.228 --> 39:59.329
I thought you should know
that he wrote it for you.

39:59.331 --> 40:01.264
6:00 a.M. --

40:01.266 --> 40:05.602
It's the time
you were born.

40:05.604 --> 40:09.272
He wanted to celebrate
the birth of his baby girl.

40:09.274 --> 40:13.576
[ inhales sharply ]

40:25.156 --> 40:28.658
<i>[ chopin's "nocturne in e-flat</i>
<i>major, op. 9 no. 2" playing ]</i>

40:34.565 --> 40:36.566
Unusual musical choice.

40:36.568 --> 40:37.967
Well, I just wanted
to reassure you

40:37.969 --> 40:40.236
That not <i>all</i> of
your cultural indoctrination

40:40.238 --> 40:41.938
Was in vain.

40:41.940 --> 40:43.373
Just most of it.

40:43.375 --> 40:44.841
How comforting.

40:47.044 --> 40:48.411
Although I must admit,

40:48.413 --> 40:51.047
I've developed
a new appreciation for jazz.

40:51.049 --> 40:55.919
Perhaps it's not all chaos
and dissonance.

40:55.921 --> 40:57.220
Just most of it.

40:57.222 --> 40:58.721
<i>¶</i>

40:58.723 --> 41:01.791
Sure is more fun
to play.

41:08.499 --> 41:10.233
Care to show me?

41:12.937 --> 41:15.171
Are you asking me
to teach you jazz?

41:17.208 --> 41:19.676
[ chuckles ]

41:19.678 --> 41:21.578
All right, so it's important
to remember that

41:21.580 --> 41:25.248
Playing jazz is about feel,
all right? Mm?

41:25.250 --> 41:27.016
[ grunts ]

41:27.018 --> 41:30.520
[ playing erroll garner's
"boogie woogie boogie" ]

41:32.156 --> 41:34.891
<i>Henry: It has been said</i>
<i>that a man is not dead</i>

41:34.893 --> 41:37.327
While his name is still spoken,

41:37.329 --> 41:39.696
<i>That we are only truly gone</i>
<i>when we've disappeared</i>

41:39.698 --> 41:42.632
<i>From the memories</i>
<i>of those who loved us,</i>

41:42.634 --> 41:45.835
<i>Meaning a great artist</i>
<i>never dies.</i>

41:45.837 --> 41:48.972
<i>As long as his books are read,</i>
<i>his paintings admired,</i>

41:48.974 --> 41:54.611
<i>As long as our songs are sung,</i>
<i>we may each of us live forever.</i>

41:54.613 --> 41:56.513
¶

41:56.515 --> 42:01.384
<i>As for me, maybe it's time</i>
<i>to learn a new song.</i>

42:01.386 --> 42:05.989
<i>Fortunately,</i>
<i>I have an excellent teacher.</i>

42:05.991 --> 42:07.290
Uh-huh.

42:07.292 --> 42:10.593
¶

42:10.595 --> 42:13.463
Yeah. [ laughs ]

42:13.465 --> 42:18.167
Go, man, go! Yeah!

42:18.169 --> 42:19.936
[ laughs ] whoo.

42:19.938 --> 42:24.307
¶
